    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-425743">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-425743">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,425743)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-425743">
																		Re:
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ekzentric-lohner" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(283423); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=283423&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204484" alt="Ekzentric Lohner" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=283423)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ekzentric-lohner" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(283423); return false;" >Ekzentric Lohner</a></span> <span class="odate time_1237776740 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">23 Mar 2009 02:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-425743">
									

<p>Agreed. I always figured Class A Amnesiacs were more than just a drug, but in the sense of being something very advanced, possibly derived or reverse-engineered from something SCP-level.</p>
<p>Torture, drugs, and hypnosis are <em>all</em> unreliable. Whatever the Foundation uses when it has to be really, <em>really</em> sure people forget, it can't be any real-world method, so I figured Class A Amnesiacs would have to be a super-version of one of those three. And a super-drug is more convenient than super-hypnosis or super-torture - you don't have to spend years learning to do it right and it can be carried around and used in the field. Seriously, if it's a long, drawn-out, horrific process that can wear off anyway, why would the Foundation bother using it instead of just <em>terminating people?</em></p>
<p>Plus, the Foundation has to carry out procedure 110-Montauk <em>every day</em>. If Class A Amnesiac = long period of torture, that raises two problems:</p>
<ol>
<li>How could the Foundation have <em>time</em> to "administer Class A Amnesiacs" before hand?</li>
<li>Can you really torture someone to remove memories of torture in order to make the next torture more effective? I'd expect it to reduce her emotional response to 110-Montauk <em>even more</em>, not <em>preserve</em> it.</li>
</ol>
<p>Echoing other posts, though, maybe this is what Class A Amnesiacs <em>used</em> to be. Maybe all those former patients didn't end up in the same place by accident - maybe Dr. Glut is about to become the last recipient of the old version, starting with something to cause a psychological breakdown, so the Foundation can cover up a darker part of it's past.</p>
<p>That said, yeah, it's really well-written.</p>

							</div>

								
					
