			<div class="content" id="post-content-425010">
									

<blockquote>
<p>And of course, it doesn't contradict anything, because Class A Amnesiac is a cover up, its doublespeak, and its inclusion in any article is paradigm manipulation. We have data expunged, of course other things are altered as well, and probably in a less noticeable way.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Um … have you actually <em>read</em> <a href="/scp-231">SCP-231</a>? A lot of the creepiness of that article hangs on the idea that people who participated its in containment have their memories erased. To quote directly -</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Yes, staff members who have been assigned to SCP-231 are allowed to take a Class A Amnesiac before leaving the project if so desired. Yes, false memories are then implanted. No, none of the supposed methods for recovering or detecting false memories work. Yes, there are some of you who've worked on SCP-231 and don't remember it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What you're suggesting would remove about 50% of the creep factor from that article. And on a more general note, I personally find the idea of mind rape a lot more disturbing than physical torture, and I suspect I'm not alone in that. To me, this just seems like an attempt to make the Foundation even more eeeeeeeeeviiiiiiiiiil than it already is, which is frankly unnecessary.</p>
<p>All that said, however, I agree with Kain that it's a very well-written story. My objection is solely to its inclusion within the SCP "canon", not to the quality of the writing. Heck, if you filed off the serial numbers and presented it just as a story about some nameless MIB-style agency, you'd probably have the basis for sellable short story.</p>

							</div>

								
					
